ğŸ§­ CIA Triad â€“ The Three Pillars of Cybersecurity
The CIA Triad is a foundational model that defines the three main goals of information security:
C â€“ Confidentiality, I â€“ Integrity, and A â€“ Availability.
It ensures that information is protected, accurate, and accessible to authorized users only.

ğŸ”’ 1ï¸âƒ£ Confidentiality
Definition:
Ensures that information is accessible only to authorized people or systems and not disclosed to unauthorized entities.
Protects sensitive data from unauthorized viewing, copying, or sharing.
Goal:
Prevent unauthorized access, data breaches, or information leaks.
How Itâ€™s Achieved:


Encryption: Converts data into unreadable format unless decrypted by an authorized key.
Examples: HTTPS, AES, RSA, SSL/TLS


Access Control: Only authorized users can access data.
Examples: RBAC, MFA


Data Classification: Labeling data (Confidential, Secret, Public) for proper protection.


Network Security: Firewalls, VPNs, IDS/IPS to block unauthorized access.


Example:
If a company encrypts all employee data (like salaries or SSNs), even if a hacker steals the database, they canâ€™t read it without the key.
â†’ Confidentiality is maintained.

ğŸ§¾ 2ï¸âƒ£ Integrity
Definition:
Ensures that information remains accurate, complete, and unaltered â€” whether stored or transmitted.
Goal:
Protect data from being tampered with or changed accidentally or maliciously.
How Itâ€™s Achieved:


Hashing: Generates a unique hash for data; if data changes, the hash changes.
Examples: SHA-256, MD5


Digital Signatures: Verify authenticity and integrity of communication.


Checksums and CRCs: Detect accidental corruption.


Version Control: Track changes (e.g., Git).


Access Control & Logging: Allow only authorized edits and track all changes.


Example:
When a fileâ€™s SHA-256 hash is verified and doesnâ€™t match, it means the file was altered.
â†’ Integrity is lost.

âš™ï¸ 3ï¸âƒ£ Availability
Definition:
Ensures that information and resources are accessible to authorized users whenever needed.
Goal:
Provide uninterrupted access to data, systems, and services.
How Itâ€™s Achieved:


Redundancy: Backup systems (RAID, load balancers, failover).


Regular Backups: Multiple copies of data.


Disaster Recovery: Ensure business continuity after failure.


Network Monitoring: Detect downtime or DDoS.


System Maintenance: Patch systems regularly.


Example:
If a DDoS attack brings a site down, availability is lost.
Load balancers and redundant servers keep services online.
â†’ Availability is maintained.

ğŸ§© Summary Table
ElementDefinitionGoalExample ControlsReal-Life ExampleğŸ”’ ConfidentialityKeep data privatePrevent unauthorized accessEncryption, MFA, Access ControlEncrypting passwords in a databaseğŸ§¾ IntegrityKeep data accuratePrevent unauthorized changesHashing, Digital Signatures, LoggingVerifying file hash before installâš™ï¸ AvailabilityKeep data accessibleEnsure continuous accessBackups, Redundancy, DDoS ProtectionServer clusters handling website traffic

ğŸ” How They Work Together
The CIA Triad elements are interdependent â€” balance is crucial:


Focusing only on confidentiality may reduce availability.


Prioritizing availability may weaken confidentiality.


Integrity ensures that whatâ€™s available is also trustworthy.


âœ… The best security strategy balances all three pillars.

ğŸ§  Quick Analogy
Imagine a bank:


Confidentiality: Only account holders and authorized staff can view balances.


Integrity: The balance shown must be accurate â€” no unauthorized edits.


Availability: ATMs and online banking must always work.


If any one fails, the systemâ€™s security is compromised.

ğŸŒ OSI Model (Open Systems Interconnection Model)

The OSI model explains how data moves through a network â€” from your computer to another device â€” in 7 layers.
Each layer has a specific job, and attackers can target each layer differently to steal, change, or block data.

ğŸ§© 1ï¸âƒ£ Physical Layer

Function: Sends raw bits (0s and 1s) over cables or Wi-Fi.
Attacks:

Wiretapping / Sniffing: Attacker physically connects to cables or Wi-Fi to capture signals.

Jamming: Blocks or interferes with wireless signals.
Goal: Steal data directly from the physical connection.
Prevention: Lock network rooms, disable unused ports, use encrypted communication (like HTTPS or VPN).

ğŸ§© 2ï¸âƒ£ Data Link Layer

Function: Moves data within the same local network using MAC addresses.
Attacks:

MAC Spoofing: Attacker changes their MAC address to impersonate another device.

ARP Poisoning: Redirects traffic through the attacker.
Goal: Intercept or control local network communication.
Prevention: Use port security, VLANs, and ARP protection on switches.

ğŸ§© 3ï¸âƒ£ Network Layer

Function: Handles IP addresses and routing of data between networks.
Attacks:

IP Spoofing: Fake IP address to hide identity or bypass firewalls.

Man-in-the-Middle: Attacker sits between two systems and reads or changes data.
Goal: Misdirect or intercept data while it travels across networks.
Prevention: Use firewalls, VPNs, and secure routing protocols.

ğŸ§© 4ï¸âƒ£ Transport Layer

Function: Ensures reliable communication (using TCP/UDP).
Attacks:

DDoS / SYN Flood: Floods a server with fake requests to crash it.

Session Hijacking: Attacker takes control of an ongoing connection.
Goal: Disrupt or take over communication sessions.
Prevention: Use firewalls, rate limiting, and encryption (TLS).

ğŸ§© 5ï¸âƒ£ Session Layer

Function: Starts, manages, and ends connections (sessions) between apps.
Attacks:

Session Hijacking / Sidejacking: Steals session tokens or cookies to impersonate a user.
Goal: Take control of user sessions.
Prevention: Use HTTPS, secure cookies, and MFA.

ğŸ§© 6ï¸âƒ£ Presentation Layer

Function: Converts, encrypts, or compresses data for apps (formats, SSL/TLS).
Attacks:

SSL Stripping: Converts HTTPS to HTTP to read data in plain text.

Malware Injection: Inserts harmful code in files or formats.
Goal: Remove encryption or inject bad data.
Prevention: Use strong TLS encryption and keep software updated.

ğŸ§© 7ï¸âƒ£ Application Layer

Function: Closest to the user â€” includes browsers, email, websites, etc.
Attacks:

SQL Injection, XSS, Phishing, Malware.
Goal: Steal data or trick users.
Prevention: Input validation, security updates, and user awareness.

